00:03:59.580 --> 00:04:03.580
[Amit Varma]: General Menon, one of the most fascinating things about your bio data, which I found,

00:04:03.580 --> 00:04:07.420
[Amit Varma]: which is like so impressive, the things that you've done in your 40 years of Army service

00:04:07.420 --> 00:04:09.940
[Amit Varma]: is the fact that you're also a PhD.

00:04:09.940 --> 00:04:15.500
[Amit Varma]: You've done a doctorate, in fact, in the very subject that you later expanded into this

00:04:15.500 --> 00:04:17.380
[Amit Varma]: book, the strategy trap.

00:04:17.380 --> 00:04:20.060
[Amit Varma]: Tell us a little bit about how that came about.

00:04:20.060 --> 00:04:30.780
[Guest]: Yeah, actually, my PhD is by default, in the sense that it was triggered by a discussion

00:04:30.780 --> 00:04:36.620
[Guest]: when I was an instructor in Staff College when India had just gone become a nuclear

00:04:36.620 --> 00:04:42.980
[Guest]: power and we have this practice in Staff College where a senior officer who comes to address

00:04:42.980 --> 00:04:48.420
[Guest]: the college has a discussion with the what we call directing staff, which is the instructional

00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:49.420
[Guest]: staff there.

00:04:49.420 --> 00:04:53.400
[Guest]: So there was this discussion and I was part of that discussion.

00:04:53.400 --> 00:04:57.780
[Guest]: And during the discussion, the discussion was about now that India has gone nuclear,

00:04:57.780 --> 00:05:01.220
[Guest]: what does it mean for the Indian Armed Forces?

00:05:01.220 --> 00:05:07.020
[Guest]: During that discussion, I realized that what I instinctively thought about the fact that

00:05:07.020 --> 00:05:14.660
[Guest]: we've gone nuclear would make a lot of difference to what the armed forces can do was quite

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:18.780
[Guest]: different from what most of them, in fact, all of them said.

00:05:18.780 --> 00:05:24.120
[Guest]: And I was a sole voice who said that now things are going to be profoundly different.

00:05:24.120 --> 00:05:28.860
[Guest]: And at one stage, in fact, I was given a shut up call by the commandant because I was arguing

00:05:28.860 --> 00:05:34.100
[Guest]: with the senior general of the army who was saying that nothing is going to be I mean,

00:05:34.100 --> 00:05:35.300
[Guest]: everything is going to be the same.

00:05:35.300 --> 00:05:37.900
[Guest]: And I was saying, no, it's not the case.

00:05:37.900 --> 00:05:46.100
[Guest]: So that I think was a trigger, which actually finally led me to my PhD, because I said,

00:05:46.100 --> 00:05:47.780
[Guest]: I must find out.

00:05:47.780 --> 00:05:50.060
[Guest]: And then I had a long journey.

00:05:50.060 --> 00:05:55.980
[Guest]: I could do my PhD because I took two years of study leave.

00:05:55.980 --> 00:06:02.140
[Guest]: I located myself in this beautiful place called Bangalore, although I was doing a PhD from

00:06:02.140 --> 00:06:08.300
[Guest]: Madras University, because I was doing a project with NIAS, which is funded by the Department

00:06:08.300 --> 00:06:10.540
[Guest]: of Atomic Energy.

00:06:10.540 --> 00:06:16.500
[Guest]: And it was a project which is congruent to my thesis of what is the impact of nuclear

00:06:16.500 --> 00:06:17.500
[Guest]: weapons.

00:06:17.500 --> 00:06:23.140
[Guest]: And I traveled and traveled all over India, I met people discussed with them, traveled

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:30.020
[Guest]: to the United States, I went to both the coasts, spoke to people in think tanks, but all their

00:06:30.020 --> 00:06:32.620
[Guest]: frame was primarily of the Cold War.

00:06:32.620 --> 00:06:38.660
[Guest]: So while there were some commonalities, I found that the Indo-Pak situation, the context

00:06:38.660 --> 00:06:41.900
[Guest]: demanded a different look.

00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:47.060
[Guest]: So two years passed, study leave was over.

00:06:47.060 --> 00:06:50.960
[Guest]: And I had not yet started on my PhD.

00:06:50.960 --> 00:06:55.860
[Guest]: My thesis was in my head actually, but I had not yet put it down on paper, I had a lot

00:06:55.860 --> 00:06:57.460
[Guest]: of notes.

00:06:57.460 --> 00:07:02.980
[Guest]: And then suddenly everything gets over, I completed the project with DAE.

00:07:02.980 --> 00:07:06.740
[Guest]: And it was a classified project, it still is.

00:07:06.740 --> 00:07:14.580
[Guest]: And then I went off to command a brigade in North Kashmir, I commanded the Haji Pir Brigade.

00:07:14.580 --> 00:07:18.860
[Guest]: And soon enough came our Parakram.

00:07:18.860 --> 00:07:23.580
[Guest]: And according to my thesis, our Parakram could not happen the way it was being planned.

00:07:23.580 --> 00:07:27.180
[Guest]: It was planned for being a big war.

00:07:27.180 --> 00:07:32.780
[Guest]: And according to me, such big wars are no longer possible between India and Pakistan.

00:07:32.780 --> 00:07:35.820
[Guest]: So my thesis survived.

00:07:35.820 --> 00:07:40.020
[Guest]: And actually Parakram because nothing happened.

00:07:40.020 --> 00:07:45.620
[Guest]: We finally demobilized.

00:07:45.620 --> 00:07:51.660
[Guest]: But I couldn't write my thesis and my professor by which time was telling me that I'm running

00:07:51.660 --> 00:07:57.180
[Guest]: out of time, that you have to complete your thesis because they have some certain regulations,

00:07:57.180 --> 00:07:58.860
[Guest]: university regulations and so on.

00:07:58.860 --> 00:08:01.620
[Guest]: And I was promising him that I'll do it.

00:08:01.620 --> 00:08:06.740
[Guest]: But there was no time that you could command a brigade in active operations.

00:08:06.740 --> 00:08:12.900
[Guest]: We were also involved heavily in counterinsurgency that I could write my thesis.

00:08:12.900 --> 00:08:20.620
[Guest]: So two years passed, but my professor was good enough, who understood the situation,

00:08:20.620 --> 00:08:26.700
[Guest]: sort of he managed to play around with the rules of the university and gave me some more

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:33.060
[Guest]: time till I went to my next appointment as the Centre Commandant, where also it was not

00:08:33.060 --> 00:08:34.140
[Guest]: possible for me to do.

00:08:34.140 --> 00:08:39.340
[Guest]: I ran into, I learned the contonement act instead of looking at my thesis because I

00:08:39.340 --> 00:08:45.180
[Guest]: was trying to sort out what I thought was a corrupt officer from the Indian Defence

00:08:45.180 --> 00:08:48.300
[Guest]: State Service.

00:08:48.300 --> 00:08:51.580
[Guest]: And my time, eight months there passed like that before that.

00:08:51.580 --> 00:08:57.820
[Guest]: But I thought I'd sorted that officer out, but nothing happened to my thesis.

00:08:57.820 --> 00:09:02.940
[Guest]: And I went on to my next, this thing on a course in Delhi, the National Defence College.

00:09:02.940 --> 00:09:09.540
[Guest]: And in the National Defence College, I could do a lot of reading and writing about what

00:09:09.540 --> 00:09:12.460
[Guest]: it is, but the thesis took a long time.

00:09:12.460 --> 00:09:17.780
[Guest]: So it was, I started writing it there and it took some sort of shape, but it was not

00:09:17.780 --> 00:09:20.740
[Guest]: in the shape it could be presented.

00:09:20.740 --> 00:09:23.340
[Guest]: And then after one year, of course, I was posted back there.

00:09:23.340 --> 00:09:25.260
[Guest]: I did some more work.

00:09:25.260 --> 00:09:30.780
[Guest]: Then I was promoted and I was sent to South Kashmir where I was a GOC.

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:36.300
[Guest]: And that's the time when my professor gave me a deadline and he said, if you don't

00:09:36.300 --> 00:09:41.620
[Guest]: complete by so and so date, your thesis cannot be accepted by the university.

00:09:41.620 --> 00:09:50.700
[Guest]: So as a commanding general of an active counterinsurgency force in Kashmir, I had an early riser, used

00:09:50.700 --> 00:09:54.140
[Guest]: to get up very early in the morning, which I normally did.

00:09:54.140 --> 00:09:59.380
[Guest]: And I used to spend the time writing my thesis and that's how I completed my thesis in

00:09:59.380 --> 00:10:00.740
[Guest]: service.

00:10:00.740 --> 00:10:09.740
[Guest]: And it's not the case that I wanted to do a PhD, but I think if not for that original

00:10:09.740 --> 00:10:15.980
[Guest]: discussion at the DSSC and my dissent, because all the time was also involved with making

00:10:15.980 --> 00:10:23.620
[Guest]: plans, which according to me, cannot possibly be actually see fruition because they were

00:10:23.620 --> 00:10:27.700
[Guest]: dangerous and actually will not achieve what we want to achieve.

00:10:27.700 --> 00:10:33.860
[Guest]: So he was a guy actually at the operational level in official capacity, making being part

00:10:33.860 --> 00:10:37.220
[Guest]: of a process that I didn't believe in.

00:10:37.220 --> 00:10:42.380
[Guest]: And therefore my PhD became an antithesis of my official life.

00:10:42.380 --> 00:10:48.460
[Amit Varma]: So your thesis was an antithesis to sort of and I mean, I find the whole subject very

00:10:48.460 --> 00:10:52.940
[Amit Varma]: fascinating in the sense of, of course, we all know that, you know, when two nuclear

00:10:52.940 --> 00:10:57.780
[Amit Varma]: powers face off, there's a concept of nuclear deterrence, and that prevents them going from

00:10:57.780 --> 00:10:58.780
[Amit Varma]: war.

00:10:58.780 --> 00:11:03.460
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, how you use forces sort of changes and is collaborated.

00:11:03.460 --> 00:11:07.860
[Amit Varma]: But what you have done is you've located all of that in the context of the subcontinent

00:11:07.860 --> 00:11:12.700
[Amit Varma]: and the particular challenges that we face that India is nuclear, Pakistan is nuclear,

00:11:12.700 --> 00:11:14.140
[Amit Varma]: China is nuclear.

00:11:14.140 --> 00:11:19.620
[Amit Varma]: And your main thrust, if I am not mistaken, and stating it this way, is that the way we

00:11:19.620 --> 00:11:25.900
[Amit Varma]: use conventional force has changed so drastically, that it is impossible to use it in anything

00:11:25.900 --> 00:11:28.260
[Amit Varma]: but the most limited way.

00:11:28.260 --> 00:11:32.740
[Amit Varma]: And this most limited way will then also be relatively ineffective.

00:11:32.740 --> 00:11:38.380
[Amit Varma]: And this presents a conundrum for us, for army and military strategists.

00:11:38.380 --> 00:11:39.700
[Guest]: Is that a correct summation?

00:11:39.700 --> 00:11:40.700
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:11:40.700 --> 00:11:45.980
[Guest]: In the fact, see, one of the problems with nuclear weapons has done to the armed forces

00:11:45.980 --> 00:11:50.340
[Guest]: of all countries is to question their relevance.

00:11:50.340 --> 00:11:52.540
[Guest]: That why do you need it anymore?

00:11:52.540 --> 00:11:56.460
[Guest]: And that's the question which has been challenged.

00:11:56.460 --> 00:12:02.700
[Guest]: Because the problem is there are two parallel paradigms which run.

00:12:02.700 --> 00:12:06.860
[Guest]: One is if you are a nuclear power, and if you're being faced with another nuclear power,

00:12:06.860 --> 00:12:13.900
[Guest]: the paradigm says that your main aim is war prevention, to prevent war.

00:12:13.900 --> 00:12:18.660
[Guest]: Nuclear weapons are meant not for use, but to prevent it.

00:12:18.660 --> 00:12:26.420
[Guest]: And that's what Bernard Brody, in the initial phase of the late 40s, first propounded.

00:12:26.420 --> 00:12:32.620
[Guest]: That the sole purpose of nuclear weapons is to prevent war.

00:12:32.620 --> 00:12:38.340
[Guest]: But in the real world, there is conventional force which is there.

00:12:38.340 --> 00:12:47.900
[Guest]: And conventional force believes in the paradigm of achieving what you call decisive victories.

00:12:47.900 --> 00:12:56.180
[Guest]: So the real world is that you have this need for preventing big war, but you also have

00:12:56.180 --> 00:13:02.620
[Guest]: these conventional forces which all the time are planning to be used for decisive victories.

00:13:02.620 --> 00:13:07.620
[Guest]: So the two divergent thoughts, but they run parallel.

00:13:07.620 --> 00:13:13.940
[Guest]: And that is what has challenged all the armies of the world ever since nuclear weapons have

00:13:13.940 --> 00:13:19.300
[Guest]: come to power in India and the Pakistani armies can be no different.

00:13:19.300 --> 00:13:25.340
[Amit Varma]: So I'm going to quote a little bit from your introduction, where you talk about, I'll just

00:13:25.340 --> 00:13:29.540
[Amit Varma]: quote this bit, start quote, after the Kargil conflict, three schools of thought emerged

00:13:29.540 --> 00:13:30.780
[Amit Varma]: in India.

00:13:30.780 --> 00:13:34.500
[Amit Varma]: Some believed that a conventional war with Pakistan is no longer practical because of

00:13:34.500 --> 00:13:38.340
[Amit Varma]: the possibility of the war escalating beyond the nuclear threshold.

00:13:38.340 --> 00:13:41.060
[Amit Varma]: And that matches Pakistan's official view.

00:13:41.060 --> 00:13:45.340
[Amit Varma]: Others are of the view that a war limited in space, time and objectives is possible.

00:13:45.340 --> 00:13:49.420
[Amit Varma]: And Kargil was cited in support of the argument, which has also been India's official view.

00:13:49.420 --> 00:13:54.780
[Amit Varma]: A third group believes that a full fledged conventional war is possible because Pakistan's

00:13:54.780 --> 00:14:00.100
[Amit Varma]: nuclear threats are bluffs that must be called since Pakistan could well be decimated, even

00:14:00.100 --> 00:14:05.500
[Amit Varma]: though we could also suffer severe damage, close quote.

00:14:05.500 --> 00:14:09.220
[Amit Varma]: Out of these three views, which is closest to what you believe?

00:14:09.220 --> 00:14:17.060
[Guest]: The first one, which is that actually the utility of force is now in question, because

00:14:17.060 --> 00:14:23.780
[Guest]: if you want to use force and a military actually is an instrument of politics, it's applied

00:14:23.780 --> 00:14:28.140
[Guest]: against the adversary to achieve political objectives.

00:14:28.140 --> 00:14:34.020
[Guest]: And those political objectives is about finally about getting the enemy to do through force

00:14:34.020 --> 00:14:40.820
[Guest]: what you want them to do to change their behavior or to do something which you which you don't

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:41.820
[Guest]: want them to do.

00:14:41.820 --> 00:14:47.460
[Guest]: So if that is the case, and in the India-Pakistan situation, I think it's very clear that what

00:14:47.460 --> 00:14:54.900
[Guest]: India wants to do, achieve politically is how do you stop Pakistan from using terror

00:14:54.900 --> 00:15:00.900
[Guest]: as a policy instrument of the state?

00:15:00.900 --> 00:15:05.700
[Guest]: And can that therefore be done by India going to war with Pakistan with conventional forces

00:15:05.700 --> 00:15:06.700
[Guest]: with conventional forces?

00:15:06.700 --> 00:15:15.980
[Guest]: I, in fact, totally I sort of discount the idea of limited nuclear war, because in my

00:15:15.980 --> 00:15:23.020
[Guest]: view, if nuclear weapons are used, then it will be extremely difficult to control the

00:15:23.020 --> 00:15:30.060
[Guest]: escalation and therefore I also talk about when Pakistan is talking about tactical nuclear

00:15:30.060 --> 00:15:31.220
[Guest]: weapons.

00:15:31.220 --> 00:15:37.700
[Guest]: And normally the example given is that Pakistan uses tactical nuclear weapons on us, because

00:15:37.700 --> 00:15:45.060
[Guest]: we have penetrated into their, I mean, our armoured spearheads have gone into that country,

00:15:45.060 --> 00:15:48.740
[Guest]: and therefore they are in danger and they can use tactical nuclear weapons.

00:15:48.740 --> 00:15:54.420
[Guest]: And they expect that India would probably give a proportionate reply, but that's not

00:15:54.420 --> 00:15:56.540
[Guest]: what the Indian doctrine says.

00:15:56.540 --> 00:16:02.340
[Guest]: Indian doctrine believes that if nuclear weapons are used, and we don't believe in the concept

00:16:02.340 --> 00:16:10.220
[Guest]: of tactical nuclear weapons, because no use of nuclear weapons can have a tactical effect.

00:16:10.220 --> 00:16:15.820
[Guest]: And that is what classifies weapons as tactical or strategic.

00:16:15.820 --> 00:16:22.820
[Guest]: And I quote an example in the book that there's nothing, no weapon is strategic or tactical

00:16:22.820 --> 00:16:24.580
[Guest]: by itself.

00:16:24.580 --> 00:16:29.100
[Guest]: It is in the effect that it creates that it can be used strategically or it can be used

00:16:29.100 --> 00:16:30.660
[Guest]: tactically.

00:16:30.660 --> 00:16:34.740
[Guest]: And the example I quote is about somebody shooting the President of the United States

00:16:34.740 --> 00:16:36.140
[Guest]: of America.

00:16:36.140 --> 00:16:42.980
[Guest]: The effect would be strategic, but that doesn't mean the pistol, which has been used is strategic.

00:16:42.980 --> 00:16:49.140
[Guest]: It has been used strategically, for strategic effect, though it is the effect which matters.

00:16:49.140 --> 00:16:53.540
[Guest]: So if a nuclear weapon, tactical nuclear weapon, as Pakistan says, is used, the effect will

00:16:53.540 --> 00:16:58.980
[Guest]: be strategic, because of the fact that it will be used against us for the first time,

00:16:58.980 --> 00:17:04.540
[Guest]: somebody has used it in war for the first time, it will have a worldwide reverberation.

00:17:04.540 --> 00:17:10.500
[Guest]: And to expect that the Indians will trust the Pakistanis that if they give a proportionate

00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:18.340
[Guest]: response, Pakistan will also now respond again proportionately, would be actually asking

00:17:18.340 --> 00:17:24.020
[Guest]: too much during that period of crisis of a leader who would be confronted with this problem

00:17:24.020 --> 00:17:29.060
[Guest]: that how do we now minimize damage to ourselves?

00:17:29.060 --> 00:17:32.940
[Guest]: If they use tactical nuclear weapons, and we use tactical nuclear weapons, or we don't

00:17:32.940 --> 00:17:38.180
[Guest]: have them, or we use them tactically for whatever way that we want to, how do we know that the

00:17:38.180 --> 00:17:41.060
[Guest]: Pakistanis will not visit us with whatever they have?

00:17:41.060 --> 00:17:43.320
[Guest]: We would suffer greater damage.

00:17:43.320 --> 00:17:47.780
[Guest]: So the decision left to the political leader is, does he want to take this risk?

00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:53.260
[Guest]: Or would he now like to make sure that he hits them so hard that you minimize damage

00:17:53.260 --> 00:17:54.660
[Guest]: to yourself?

00:17:54.660 --> 00:18:00.980
[Guest]: So these are issues which can actually never be answered fully, because only a person put

00:18:00.980 --> 00:18:06.000
[Guest]: in that situation will have to decide how do you use it.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:12.780
[Guest]: So the Indian doctrine has some sort of flexibility on how to confront this sort of problem which

00:18:12.780 --> 00:18:20.220
[Guest]: we have, that anybody who uses nuclear weapons on us can expect that we will retaliate and

00:18:20.220 --> 00:18:22.460
[Guest]: that's a credible threat.

00:18:22.460 --> 00:18:27.180
[Guest]: The less credible threat is Pakistan telling us they will use it first.

00:18:27.180 --> 00:18:31.380
[Guest]: Because how will they use it first when they know that we can actually retaliate?

00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:37.220
[Guest]: And a tactical nuclear weapon has this problem that if they use it in a small measure, then

00:18:37.220 --> 00:18:41.340
[Guest]: our nuclear weapons are intact.

00:18:41.340 --> 00:18:50.140
[Guest]: And therefore, we have the advantage of actually reply them with much greater response, which

00:18:50.140 --> 00:18:52.820
[Guest]: can hurt them more than what they want to achieve.

00:18:52.820 --> 00:18:56.980
[Guest]: So you know, these are the dilemmas of use of weapons.

00:18:56.980 --> 00:18:59.180
[Guest]: Any use of weapon is actually impractical.

00:18:59.180 --> 00:19:02.480
[Guest]: So it cannot be used by a rational action.

00:19:02.480 --> 00:19:06.660
[Amit Varma]: This is actually a very profound point and eye opening for me this distinction that you've

00:19:06.660 --> 00:19:09.380
[Amit Varma]: made between the tactical use and the strategic use.

00:19:09.380 --> 00:19:13.500
[Amit Varma]: And we've often heard of tactical nuclear weapons and you just explained beautifully

00:19:13.500 --> 00:19:16.340
[Amit Varma]: why it's not possible for the benefit of my listeners.

00:19:16.340 --> 00:19:20.020
[Amit Varma]: I'll just elaborate on what you mean by tactical and strategic and tell me if I'm doing that

00:19:20.020 --> 00:19:24.660
[Amit Varma]: correctly tactical is you have a limited short term objective, like say someone's occupied

00:19:24.660 --> 00:19:27.420
[Amit Varma]: a particular area and you want to get them out of there.

00:19:27.420 --> 00:19:33.380
[Amit Varma]: And what you do to achieve that limited end is tactical and strategic is a larger objective

00:19:33.380 --> 00:19:36.760
[Amit Varma]: of the war as it were a larger long term objective.

00:19:36.760 --> 00:19:41.740
[Amit Varma]: And your point is that even if they use or rather the Indian point of view here is that

00:19:41.740 --> 00:19:46.140
[Amit Varma]: even if they use a nuclear weapon for what seems to be the limited objective, that army

00:19:46.140 --> 00:19:50.620
[Amit Varma]: ko yahan se bhagao, it will have strategic repercussions because it will change the way

00:19:50.620 --> 00:19:56.580
[Amit Varma]: not just India but the whole the way the whole world views that particular engagement and

00:19:56.580 --> 00:20:00.260
[Amit Varma]: it will just change the paradigm of India Pakistan relations.

00:20:00.260 --> 00:20:01.260
[Guest]: Yeah, right.

00:20:01.260 --> 00:20:06.140
[Guest]: See the basic distinction, which although there is no clear line, is the magnitude of

00:20:06.140 --> 00:20:10.740
[Guest]: the effect of using something of applying force.

00:20:10.740 --> 00:20:16.100
[Guest]: Does that magnitude of that affect your long term goals?

00:20:16.100 --> 00:20:17.380
[Guest]: That is strategic.

00:20:17.380 --> 00:20:24.780
[Guest]: The ones which are actually of a local nature, which will disappear after some time, which

00:20:24.780 --> 00:20:31.220
[Guest]: does not may impact so much, although it can have an impact on your long term goal, but

00:20:31.220 --> 00:20:35.740
[Guest]: the impact is less and that is actually what is differentiates between the tactical and

00:20:35.740 --> 00:20:36.740
[Amit Varma]: strategic.

00:20:36.740 --> 00:20:37.740
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:20:37.740 --> 00:20:42.980
[Amit Varma]: So what I want to do now is ask you about the different doctrines that different nuclear

00:20:42.980 --> 00:20:47.940
[Amit Varma]: nations have, like how have they formulated that but before that, what strikes me as very

00:20:47.940 --> 00:20:54.860
[Amit Varma]: interesting is that because we have almost a non existent sample size of nuclear nations

00:20:54.860 --> 00:20:59.000
[Amit Varma]: actually getting into conflicts with each other, all of these doctrines and everything

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:03.780
[Amit Varma]: that we understand about the subject is in the realm of theory.

00:21:03.780 --> 00:21:07.820
[Amit Varma]: Practically what happens and you use a famous phrase of fog of war in the conversation we

00:21:07.820 --> 00:21:11.940
[Amit Varma]: were happening just before we started recording and in practical terms, what will happen in

00:21:11.940 --> 00:21:17.740
[Amit Varma]: the fog of war, you know, when war actually begins and one event leads to another is something

00:21:17.740 --> 00:21:20.260
[Amit Varma]: that hasn't been tested yet.

00:21:20.260 --> 00:21:22.620
[Amit Varma]: And everything therefore is in the realm of theory.

00:21:22.620 --> 00:21:25.580
[Guest]: Yeah, that's the problem actually.

00:21:25.580 --> 00:21:31.300
[Guest]: And I say this in the book, the problem with nuclear strategy is it cannot answer the question

00:21:31.300 --> 00:21:34.780
[Guest]: what happens when deterrence fails.

00:21:34.780 --> 00:21:39.980
[Guest]: See all nuclear strategy is based on the fact that it is meant to deter.

00:21:39.980 --> 00:21:48.620
[Guest]: That means it is meant to deter the other person from using nuclear weapons, but some

00:21:48.620 --> 00:21:53.020
[Guest]: doctrines of other countries and most doctrines of other countries except India and China

00:21:53.020 --> 00:22:01.180
[Guest]: believe that nuclear weapons can be threatened to be used against conventional force against

00:22:01.180 --> 00:22:10.660
[Guest]: biological and chemical weapons, but it is only India and China, which believes that

00:22:10.660 --> 00:22:14.660
[Guest]: we think that nuclear weapons can deter only their kind.

00:22:14.660 --> 00:22:20.900
[Guest]: And India also has another option for biological and chemical weapons, where in the doctrine

00:22:20.900 --> 00:22:28.980
[Guest]: we say that we retain the option for retaliating with nuclear weapons, if biological and chemical

00:22:28.980 --> 00:22:35.620
[Guest]: weapons are used against us, which means we have not committed fully to using it, which

00:22:35.620 --> 00:22:41.060
[Guest]: I think is a very wise move, because biological and chemical weapons, although we call them

00:22:41.060 --> 00:22:47.580
[Guest]: weapons of mass destruction, are actually of a different kind in the scale and the speed

00:22:47.580 --> 00:22:50.180
[Guest]: at which damage can be inflicted.

00:22:50.180 --> 00:22:54.740
[Guest]: Nuclear weapons scale and speed are unmatched by biological and chemical weapons.

00:22:54.740 --> 00:22:58.300
[Guest]: And you need a lot of biological and a lot of chemical weapons to achieve the same type

00:22:58.300 --> 00:22:59.520
[Guest]: of destruction.

00:22:59.520 --> 00:23:04.060
[Guest]: So actually speaking, they don't belong to the same basket, although they are mass.

00:23:04.060 --> 00:23:09.380
[Guest]: So India very rightly has said that we retain the option and that's how we have actually

00:23:09.380 --> 00:23:10.380
[Guest]: get there.

00:23:10.380 --> 00:23:16.140
[Guest]: So when you look at all these doctrines, one of the things which distinguishes us in China

00:23:16.140 --> 00:23:25.100
[Guest]: is that we have restricted our use of nuclear weapons to a very core deterrence role of

00:23:25.100 --> 00:23:26.740
[Guest]: nuclear weapons.

00:23:26.740 --> 00:23:36.660
[Guest]: The other nations, United States, Russia, UK, France, have all said that if they are

00:23:36.660 --> 00:23:42.140
[Guest]: attacked with conventional weapons, they threaten that they will use nuclear weapons.

00:23:42.140 --> 00:23:48.580
[Guest]: And I think so far, if we just take the North Korean example, the fact that North Korea

00:23:48.580 --> 00:23:57.620
[Guest]: is just a nuclear state in its infancy, can actually talk up and face the most powerful

00:23:57.620 --> 00:24:03.180
[Guest]: nuclear nations in the world is a lesson that you don't have to have many nuclear weapons

00:24:03.180 --> 00:24:06.060
[Guest]: to actually scare off the other guy.

00:24:06.060 --> 00:24:10.740
[Guest]: Because of the fact that the magnitude, even one nuclear weapon, which visits the United

00:24:10.740 --> 00:24:15.620
[Guest]: States of America, one of the cities, would be enough for nuclear weapons for America

00:24:15.620 --> 00:24:20.180
[Guest]: to be worried about the fact that this is what can happen to us.

00:24:20.180 --> 00:24:26.180
[Guest]: So deterrence does not demand a big scale.

00:24:26.180 --> 00:24:34.940
[Guest]: In the Cold War, more than the United States and Russia had more than 60 to 70,000 weapons.

00:24:34.940 --> 00:24:38.840
[Guest]: That was a scale because they believe that numbers mattered.

00:24:38.840 --> 00:24:40.140
[Guest]: But really numbers do not matter.

00:24:40.140 --> 00:24:43.860
[Guest]: And I think that North Korea is now an example which can be quoted that numbers do matter.

00:24:43.860 --> 00:24:48.000
[Amit Varma]: So why is it that what's the logic then behind India and China having this different sort

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:51.800
[Amit Varma]: of doctrine where they say that we will use nuclear weapons only if nuclear weapons are

00:24:51.800 --> 00:24:54.740
[Amit Varma]: used against us and maybe other WMD as you said?

00:24:54.740 --> 00:24:55.740
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:24:55.740 --> 00:25:01.020
[Guest]: See, the basic difference between India, China and the rest is, is we are two countries who

00:25:01.020 --> 00:25:05.020
[Guest]: have really not used military force for coercion.

00:25:05.020 --> 00:25:07.620
[Guest]: We have not threatened military force for coercion.

00:25:07.620 --> 00:25:08.620
[Guest]: We've used it to defend.

00:25:08.620 --> 00:25:13.220
[Guest]: Yeah, but basically, we are saying that we are military and we don't want to use nuclear

00:25:13.220 --> 00:25:15.820
[Guest]: weapons to coerce others.

00:25:15.820 --> 00:25:22.440
[Guest]: China went nuclear because America used the threat of nuclear weapons to coerce China

00:25:22.440 --> 00:25:28.500
[Guest]: soon after it became, you know, and I quote those examples when I cover the Chinese doctrine,

00:25:28.500 --> 00:25:33.760
[Guest]: where President Truman actually used them and he actually has also threatened them during

00:25:33.760 --> 00:25:35.380
[Guest]: the Korean War.

00:25:35.380 --> 00:25:40.220
[Guest]: So China is one country which has faced nuclear threats when it didn't have nuclear weapons.

00:25:40.220 --> 00:25:42.580
[Guest]: It went nuclear only in 1964.

00:25:42.580 --> 00:25:47.860
[Guest]: So it believed and Mao said this very clear that actually nuclear weapons are paper tigers.

00:25:47.860 --> 00:25:50.480
[Guest]: You can't threaten anybody with nuclear weapons.

00:25:50.480 --> 00:25:55.140
[Guest]: But if you don't have nuclear weapons, others will threaten you with nuclear weapons.

00:25:55.140 --> 00:25:57.460
[Guest]: And that is why they went nuclear.

00:25:57.460 --> 00:26:02.860
[Guest]: And that is also why India has also gone nuclear, because we were threatened with nuclear weapons

00:26:02.860 --> 00:26:06.860
[Guest]: or there was a threat which is developing from China and from Pakistan.

00:26:06.860 --> 00:26:09.140
[Guest]: Although China has never threatened us overtly.

00:26:09.140 --> 00:26:15.460
[Guest]: But the fact is, we realized that if you don't have nuclear weapons, you will be threatened.

00:26:15.460 --> 00:26:17.300
[Guest]: That means you will be coerced.

00:26:17.300 --> 00:26:19.180
[Guest]: And therefore was the need for nuclear weapons.

00:26:19.180 --> 00:26:24.820
[Guest]: And that is why India and China, Americans and Russians actually at one time, they had

00:26:24.820 --> 00:26:32.620
[Guest]: switched from after the Soviet Union broke up, they said they had embraced NFU.

00:26:32.620 --> 00:26:37.280
[Guest]: But now they've gone back again, because they say that the conventional power is weak.

00:26:37.280 --> 00:26:43.780
[Guest]: So we and China are different because we believe nuclear weapons are only meant for a defensive

00:26:43.780 --> 00:26:44.940
[Guest]: purpose.

00:26:44.940 --> 00:26:49.140
[Guest]: It is not meant to actually coerce the other and that is where the difference is.

00:26:49.140 --> 00:26:53.340
[Amit Varma]: So I have a sort of game theoretical kind of question and forgive me if it's a naive

00:26:53.340 --> 00:26:56.500
[Amit Varma]: question because I'm a newbie to the subject.

00:26:56.500 --> 00:27:01.500
[Amit Varma]: But if the whole objective of having nuclear weapons of deterrence is to avoid war so that

00:27:01.500 --> 00:27:05.500
[Amit Varma]: people are scared to attack you, then isn't it more effective?

00:27:05.500 --> 00:27:10.220
[Amit Varma]: If you don't show that restraint, and if you just say that, hey, we can use it anytime,

00:27:10.220 --> 00:27:15.220
[Amit Varma]: almost like a game of chicken, where they think that and perhaps game of North Korea

00:27:15.220 --> 00:27:19.380
[Amit Varma]: is doing exactly that, you know, he may not really be as reckless and mad as he makes

00:27:19.380 --> 00:27:20.380
[Amit Varma]: himself out to be.

00:27:20.380 --> 00:27:25.740
[Amit Varma]: But in from a game theoretical point of view, if people think he is like that, then that

00:27:25.740 --> 00:27:31.020
[Amit Varma]: will increase the credibility of the deterrence of his nuclear weapons, because I don't think

00:27:31.020 --> 00:27:34.260
[Amit Varma]: he's mad enough to just, you know, send a bomb to Seoul anytime.

00:27:34.260 --> 00:27:38.780
[Amit Varma]: So from that point of view, it strikes me as sort of counterintuitive that we would

00:27:38.780 --> 00:27:43.420
[Amit Varma]: actually impose a restraint on our use of nuclear weapons, instead of saying that, look,

00:27:43.420 --> 00:27:45.740
[Amit Varma]: if you attack us all bets off, we'll do anything.

00:27:45.740 --> 00:27:49.220
[Amit Varma]: But instead of that, if we just say that we will only use it against other weapons of

00:27:49.220 --> 00:27:56.540
[Amit Varma]: mass destruction, then in a sense, that emboldens Pakistan to use conventional weapons and you

00:27:56.540 --> 00:27:58.380
[Amit Varma]: know, other means of warfare against us.

00:27:58.380 --> 00:28:03.440
[Guest]: Yeah, actually, the situation is called a stability instability paradox.

00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:08.100
[Guest]: That when you have nuclear weapons on other both sides, then you have stability at the

00:28:08.100 --> 00:28:12.420
[Guest]: higher level, that means you will not go in for a big fight, right?

00:28:12.420 --> 00:28:16.980
[Guest]: Because of the fact that the big fight might not turn out to be both of you can get hurt

00:28:16.980 --> 00:28:18.180
[Guest]: very badly.

00:28:18.180 --> 00:28:22.860
[Guest]: So you have stability there, but you have instability at the lower level.

00:28:22.860 --> 00:28:28.580
[Guest]: So because and that's exactly what the Indian condition is, it's typical of what it is.

00:28:28.580 --> 00:28:36.380
[Guest]: And there, Pakistan is advantaged, because they can use terror as a tool of foreign policy.

00:28:36.380 --> 00:28:41.620
[Guest]: And India finds that is not able to retaliate and stop them from using it.

00:28:41.620 --> 00:28:43.860
[Guest]: So that's the instability.

00:28:43.860 --> 00:28:45.780
[Guest]: And this we are disadvantaged.

00:28:45.780 --> 00:28:46.780
[Guest]: All right.

00:28:46.780 --> 00:28:54.460
[Guest]: But let's say that suppose we also had a first use policy, I mean, the policy was first use.

00:28:54.460 --> 00:29:01.140
[Guest]: Now, this is a political decision of how you see nuclear weapons.

00:29:01.140 --> 00:29:06.700
[Guest]: India does not see nuclear weapons as meant for military use.

00:29:06.700 --> 00:29:13.180
[Guest]: It's purely a political weapon for prevent somebody from using it.

00:29:13.180 --> 00:29:18.100
[Guest]: And it is politically because one of the things about nuclear weapons is that because of the

00:29:18.100 --> 00:29:24.620
[Guest]: sheer destructive power and the magnitude and speed of destruction, anything you say

00:29:24.620 --> 00:29:30.180
[Guest]: or threaten the other nuclear weapons goes directly to the decision maker on the other

00:29:30.180 --> 00:29:31.180
[Guest]: side.

00:29:31.180 --> 00:29:33.180
[Guest]: You know, that's the magnitude of the threat.

00:29:33.180 --> 00:29:37.140
[Guest]: So you can influence that mind very well.

00:29:37.140 --> 00:29:43.260
[Guest]: You can say you can influence the mind without just issuing a small threat is enough to change

00:29:43.260 --> 00:29:44.260
[Guest]: behavior.

00:29:44.260 --> 00:29:45.260
[Guest]: So this is what it is.

00:29:45.260 --> 00:29:50.740
[Guest]: And also, we are not only India, Pakistan, this thing, we have actually got we're in

00:29:50.740 --> 00:29:55.460
[Guest]: a situation where we have got another adversary in China.

00:29:55.460 --> 00:29:58.020
[Guest]: So we have a triad here.

00:29:58.020 --> 00:30:05.340
[Guest]: So it is from the belief, the basic belief of what nuclear weapons are meant for that

00:30:05.340 --> 00:30:08.660
[Guest]: are no first use doctrine has to come into play.

00:30:08.660 --> 00:30:11.740
[Guest]: Any other thought is military in character.

00:30:11.740 --> 00:30:14.700
[Guest]: It is not political in character.

00:30:14.700 --> 00:30:18.700
[Guest]: The politics obviously is the one should guide what is military.

00:30:18.700 --> 00:30:25.180
[Guest]: See that is why all military people do not agree with the idea that no first use is a

00:30:25.180 --> 00:30:30.500
[Guest]: good thing because if militaries don't want to get hit first, they would like naturally

00:30:30.500 --> 00:30:31.500
[Guest]: to hit.

00:30:31.500 --> 00:30:35.500
[Guest]: Or at least have that credible thing.

00:30:35.500 --> 00:30:41.380
[Guest]: But the problem with nuclear weapons is that first use is not credible because even if

00:30:41.380 --> 00:30:49.380
[Guest]: you can be visited and returned by a couple of weapons, it would really you won't use

00:30:49.380 --> 00:30:50.380
[Guest]: it.

00:30:50.380 --> 00:30:52.860
[Guest]: And also there is another complexity here.

00:30:52.860 --> 00:30:58.180
[Guest]: Now that complexity comes from the fact that if there is a regional nuclear war, let's

00:30:58.180 --> 00:31:01.860
[Guest]: say we have a regional.

00:31:01.860 --> 00:31:08.260
[Guest]: Studies now indicate that the whole global it's possible that it impact the globe in

00:31:08.260 --> 00:31:10.620
[Guest]: climatically.

00:31:10.620 --> 00:31:15.500
[Guest]: And that's going to be of concern to everybody else.

00:31:15.500 --> 00:31:22.300
[Guest]: Because of the fact that firstly we are very densely populated in a space was Pakistan

00:31:22.300 --> 00:31:23.300
[Guest]: so is India.

00:31:23.300 --> 00:31:28.420
[Guest]: We are very combustible in our cities, a lot of energies reside in them.

00:31:28.420 --> 00:31:31.700
[Guest]: So the type of smoke and this thing which we are going to throw around the world will

00:31:31.700 --> 00:31:37.580
[Guest]: cause climate change, which will affect the entire globe and probably depending upon the

00:31:37.580 --> 00:31:45.380
[Guest]: intensity of what has happened, it can cause widespread biological changes, which will

00:31:45.380 --> 00:31:52.380
[Guest]: affect your food chain, your water and threaten existence and life itself because of the social

00:31:52.380 --> 00:31:55.180
[Guest]: turmoil it's going to create in the rest of the world.

00:31:55.180 --> 00:31:59.900
[Guest]: So world now knows that if India and Pakistan fights a nuclear war, it's not going to be

00:31:59.900 --> 00:32:04.140
[Guest]: contained to the effects in the subcontinent, the world is going to be affected.

00:32:04.140 --> 00:32:09.140
[Guest]: So the any idea who's saying that you know, we're going to use this first has a credibility

00:32:09.140 --> 00:32:10.500
[Guest]: problem.

00:32:10.500 --> 00:32:16.700
[Guest]: And I think India has been very wise to the fact that we don't see this at all as a military

00:32:16.700 --> 00:32:18.500
[Guest]: weapon.

00:32:18.500 --> 00:32:22.820
[Guest]: Militaries don't like this idea because militaries don't like to wait to be hit.

00:32:22.820 --> 00:32:28.380
[Guest]: And that's why the whole Dettin's theory is based on what you call second strike capability.

