[Unknown]: as well.

00:33:18.380 --> 00:33:20.620
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

00:33:20.620 --> 00:33:25.140
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Lieutenant General Prakash Menon about nuclear weapons and the use of

00:33:25.140 --> 00:33:27.940
[Amit Varma]: force and how they change the dynamic between nations.

00:33:27.940 --> 00:33:34.740
[Amit Varma]: So my question for you, General Menon, then is that if we have decided that, you know,

00:33:34.740 --> 00:33:38.860
[Amit Varma]: there's no first use doctrine and this is not a military weapon, it's a political weapon

00:33:38.860 --> 00:33:41.780
[Amit Varma]: to scare the other guy and we're never actually going to use it.

00:33:41.780 --> 00:33:45.820
[Amit Varma]: But then doesn't it become a very weak political weapon if the other guy knows that he India

00:33:45.820 --> 00:33:48.060
[Amit Varma]: is never going to use it, so it doesn't matter.

00:33:48.060 --> 00:33:53.300
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, since we are not going to retaliate to conventional attacks with

00:33:53.300 --> 00:33:58.820
[Amit Varma]: nuclear weapons, doesn't it actually in one way make us weaker because earlier we could

00:33:58.820 --> 00:34:02.720
[Amit Varma]: have engaged in unrestrained conventional warfare.

00:34:02.720 --> 00:34:06.020
[Amit Varma]: But now we can't even do that because it might escalate.

00:34:06.020 --> 00:34:09.640
[Amit Varma]: And everybody knows we're not going to use the nuclear weapons.

00:34:09.640 --> 00:34:11.140
[Amit Varma]: How does that affect the dynamic?

00:34:11.140 --> 00:34:13.780
[Guest]: No, we are not saying we won't use it.

00:34:13.780 --> 00:34:19.020
[Guest]: We are saying that we will use it if you use nuclear weapons, if the adversary uses nuclear

00:34:19.020 --> 00:34:20.020
[Guest]: weapons.

00:34:20.020 --> 00:34:27.980
[Guest]: So the fact is, we don't want to bring the nuclear weapon into the equation as far as

00:34:27.980 --> 00:34:28.980
[Guest]: war is concerned.

00:34:28.980 --> 00:34:31.380
[Guest]: We're saying that we will not use it first.

00:34:31.380 --> 00:34:32.820
[Guest]: That's the first point.

00:34:32.820 --> 00:34:41.300
[Guest]: The second point is that if you, the threat which we face today from both China and Pakistan,

00:34:41.300 --> 00:34:48.420
[Guest]: we do not intend to counter that threat through nuclear weapons.

00:34:48.420 --> 00:34:53.220
[Guest]: Because we do not believe that nuclear weapons can be used.

00:34:53.220 --> 00:34:55.500
[Guest]: That is the fundamental belief.

00:34:55.500 --> 00:35:02.140
[Guest]: Because if it is used, and if it is used between nuclear powers, it will not only affect both

00:35:02.140 --> 00:35:05.540
[Guest]: those nations, it will affect the entire globe.

00:35:05.540 --> 00:35:07.780
[Guest]: And what do Pakistan and China believe?

00:35:07.780 --> 00:35:10.020
[Guest]: China has the same belief as us.

00:35:10.020 --> 00:35:11.820
[Guest]: They believe that it's a political weapon.

00:35:11.820 --> 00:35:14.980
[Guest]: In fact, their nuclear doctrine is quite congruent to us.

00:35:14.980 --> 00:35:18.740
[Guest]: In fact, Mao said that nuclear weapons are paper tigers.

00:35:18.740 --> 00:35:22.100
[Guest]: It's a famous quote that he made.

00:35:22.100 --> 00:35:27.020
[Guest]: And so as far as China is concerned, we are on the same, we do not believe that within

00:35:27.020 --> 00:35:29.420
[Guest]: our this thing, we'll bring nuclear weapons with.

00:35:29.420 --> 00:35:33.020
[Guest]: But as far as Pakistan is concerned, it's a smaller power.

00:35:33.020 --> 00:35:36.300
[Guest]: It sees India as a bigger conventional power.

00:35:36.300 --> 00:35:42.780
[Guest]: And it believes that if it wields the threat of nuclear weapons, India will not attack

00:35:42.780 --> 00:35:45.060
[Guest]: it conventionally.

00:35:45.060 --> 00:35:52.300
[Guest]: My point is, India does not have to attack Pakistan conventionally, because now there

00:35:52.300 --> 00:35:58.720
[Guest]: is no reason for doing so, because you can't achieve much with it.

00:35:58.720 --> 00:36:06.940
[Guest]: So we must first embrace the idea that going to war with Pakistan cannot achieve anything

00:36:06.940 --> 00:36:09.060
[Guest]: much for what you actually want to fight the war.

00:36:09.060 --> 00:36:11.340
[Amit Varma]: Why do you want to go to war with Pakistan in any case?

00:36:11.340 --> 00:36:12.940
[Guest]: Why can't it achieve anything?

00:36:12.940 --> 00:36:13.940
[Guest]: Right.

00:36:13.940 --> 00:36:16.060
[Guest]: The problem is like this.

00:36:16.060 --> 00:36:20.260
[Guest]: Pakistan, the nature of the state that it is, is a jihadist country.

00:36:20.260 --> 00:36:27.180
[Guest]: It's actually controlled by the armed forces, which is in power all the time, whether it

00:36:27.180 --> 00:36:30.660
[Guest]: is officially or not.

00:36:30.660 --> 00:36:37.220
[Guest]: If you want to actually control Pakistan, or you want this thing, you will have to have

00:36:37.220 --> 00:36:41.060
[Guest]: to defeat the Pakistan armed forces.

00:36:41.060 --> 00:36:46.860
[Guest]: If you defeat the Pakistani armed forces, then you need to control the land area of

00:36:46.860 --> 00:36:48.220
[Guest]: Pakistan.

00:36:48.220 --> 00:36:50.220
[Guest]: And it's a jihadist state.

00:36:50.220 --> 00:36:57.340
[Guest]: So why would you, and unfortunately for us, if Pakistan implodes, let's say we go to war

00:36:57.340 --> 00:37:02.660
[Guest]: with Pakistan and Pakistan armed forces actually are defeated and Pakistan therefore, since

00:37:02.660 --> 00:37:06.820
[Guest]: army is in control there, Pakistan will implode.

00:37:06.820 --> 00:37:11.580
[Guest]: Let's say the, there will be complete civil disorder.

00:37:11.580 --> 00:37:16.100
[Amit Varma]: Sorry for interrupting, but if the army faces an existential threat, then they're very likely

00:37:16.100 --> 00:37:18.060
[Guest]: to just use a nuclear weapon anyway, right?

00:37:18.060 --> 00:37:19.060
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:37:19.060 --> 00:37:20.060
[Guest]: So why would you actually want to do that?

00:37:20.060 --> 00:37:22.860
[Guest]: Why would you want to put them in that position?

00:37:22.860 --> 00:37:24.180
[Guest]: What are you going to gain?

00:37:24.180 --> 00:37:29.100
[Guest]: The point is you have to relate that war as an instrument for what you want to achieve.

00:37:29.100 --> 00:37:31.420
[Guest]: Why are you going to war with Pakistan?

00:37:31.420 --> 00:37:38.260
[Guest]: If you're going to war with Pakistan to stop Pakistan from using terror as a tool of foreign

00:37:38.260 --> 00:37:44.620
[Guest]: policy, then defeating the Pakistani armed forces will make Pakistan implode.

00:37:44.620 --> 00:37:50.340
[Guest]: Jihadis probably might take over and the civilian population, we can go nowhere else because

00:37:50.340 --> 00:37:52.140
[Guest]: geography doesn't allow them.

00:37:52.140 --> 00:37:53.140
[Guest]: They will come here.

00:37:53.140 --> 00:37:55.740
[Guest]: We won't be able to stop them at the borders.

00:37:55.740 --> 00:38:02.980
[Guest]: And that probably, if you look at India's own fault line, it'll obviously deepen that

00:38:02.980 --> 00:38:06.340
[Guest]: fault line and we could be in serious trouble ourselves.

00:38:06.340 --> 00:38:10.180
[Guest]: So we have a paradox here that we call it an adversary.

00:38:10.180 --> 00:38:16.180
[Guest]: If you go to war with them, defeat them, then you might finally, you yourself will be in

00:38:16.180 --> 00:38:17.700
[Guest]: trouble because of that defeat.

00:38:17.700 --> 00:38:19.340
[Guest]: It's a paradox.

00:38:19.340 --> 00:38:22.740
[Guest]: So how do you actually now deal with this state?

00:38:22.740 --> 00:38:24.400
[Guest]: Through force.

00:38:24.400 --> 00:38:26.540
[Guest]: So is force the correct way to deal with it?

00:38:26.540 --> 00:38:30.620
[Guest]: Because if you're going to war, what is your purpose?

00:38:30.620 --> 00:38:33.020
[Guest]: And that purpose actually in this case is self-defeating.

00:38:33.020 --> 00:38:41.140
[Guest]: If you use force, and that's something which Indian political leaders need to realize.

00:38:41.140 --> 00:38:46.780
[Amit Varma]: And would it be correct to say that given the kind of terror operations that are carried

00:38:46.780 --> 00:38:53.060
[Amit Varma]: out from Pakistan against us constantly, you know, for the last couple of decades, at least

00:38:53.060 --> 00:38:57.820
[Amit Varma]: that whatever we feel about it, they are already at a state of war against us.

00:38:57.820 --> 00:39:02.780
[Amit Varma]: So my two questions would be that, does our having nuclear weapons make a difference to

00:39:02.780 --> 00:39:05.300
[Amit Varma]: how we tackle this?

00:39:05.300 --> 00:39:09.180
[Amit Varma]: And the second one would be how should we tackle this given the way things are?

00:39:09.180 --> 00:39:10.780
[Guest]: Yeah, let's put it this way.

00:39:10.780 --> 00:39:15.780
[Guest]: If we didn't have nuclear weapons, I'm sure by now we would have gone to war with Pakistan,

00:39:15.780 --> 00:39:18.100
[Guest]: let's say in 2008 and all those things.

00:39:18.100 --> 00:39:25.340
[Guest]: So probably, although it cannot be directly connected, but you must say that the just

00:39:25.340 --> 00:39:30.180
[Guest]: the emotional fuel in India about these terror attacks would have forced the politicians

00:39:30.180 --> 00:39:33.100
[Guest]: hand to actually go to war, but it hasn't happened.

00:39:33.100 --> 00:39:38.800
[Guest]: One of the reasons probably could be is that there's nuclear weapons in play here.

00:39:38.800 --> 00:39:46.740
[Guest]: But I think the main issue here is if terror is what Pakistan is going to use and terror

00:39:46.740 --> 00:39:53.540
[Guest]: is a means it's actually not something which you can say that you can stop them from using

00:39:53.540 --> 00:39:58.820
[Guest]: it because that's the means that a weak nation will use the means at its disposal.

00:39:58.820 --> 00:40:05.420
[Guest]: And Pakistan's strategy is about, you know, wounding India with a thousand cuts.

00:40:05.420 --> 00:40:06.980
[Guest]: And these are the thousand cuts.

00:40:06.980 --> 00:40:13.140
[Guest]: Now, if you look at India in the larger context, we look at ourselves, what where are we now?

00:40:13.140 --> 00:40:16.020
[Guest]: We are in the process of development.

00:40:16.020 --> 00:40:19.100
[Guest]: Our main focus is not Pakistan.

00:40:19.100 --> 00:40:22.900
[Guest]: Our main focus is our own economic and social development.

00:40:22.900 --> 00:40:28.860
[Guest]: If that is the focus, then our strategy should be not get involved with the jihadist state

00:40:28.860 --> 00:40:32.500
[Guest]: and try to reform it because we cannot.

00:40:32.500 --> 00:40:38.240
[Guest]: Our strategy should be to contain it in such a manner that it does not affect our main

00:40:38.240 --> 00:40:42.140
[Guest]: focus, which is economic and social development.

00:40:42.140 --> 00:40:49.220
[Guest]: So if we think that if we fall into the trap which Pakistan is laying out for us, then

00:40:49.220 --> 00:40:56.220
[Guest]: come and get enmeshed with them and start a ding dong battle or fight, then I think

00:40:56.220 --> 00:40:58.800
[Guest]: in strategic terms, it is not prudent.

00:40:58.800 --> 00:41:01.820
[Amit Varma]: And that's a negative sum game where we have more to lose.

00:41:01.820 --> 00:41:03.740
[Guest]: Yes, of course.

00:41:03.740 --> 00:41:10.260
[Guest]: And that is exactly what Pakistan wants in the sense that, remember, Pakistan's army's

00:41:10.260 --> 00:41:17.220
[Guest]: main strength comes from actually creating an Indian threat.

00:41:17.220 --> 00:41:22.780
[Guest]: If that Indian threat is what keeps the rest of support, the support to Pakistani army

00:41:22.780 --> 00:41:24.720
[Guest]: in that polity.

00:41:24.720 --> 00:41:29.940
[Guest]: So for them to create the Indian threat is the strengthening.

00:41:29.940 --> 00:41:36.680
[Guest]: We should be wary of when we deal with Pakistan with force, that this is what Pakistan's strategy

00:41:36.680 --> 00:41:37.980
[Guest]: and gameplay is.

00:41:37.980 --> 00:41:45.620
[Guest]: If we know this is the gameplay, then when we are hit, and I suggest that in my book,

00:41:45.620 --> 00:41:50.220
[Guest]: it is not about hitting back because we want to stop them from doing what they want to

00:41:50.220 --> 00:41:51.220
[Guest]: do.

00:41:51.220 --> 00:41:52.220
[Guest]: It is about retribution.

00:41:52.220 --> 00:41:59.060
[Guest]: It will have an impact, but we know that impact is temporary.

00:41:59.060 --> 00:42:01.940
[Guest]: But it also got another major impact.

00:42:01.940 --> 00:42:11.220
[Guest]: It is to sort of assuage the hurt feelings of India's population itself, who seeks revenge

00:42:11.220 --> 00:42:13.060
[Guest]: because of an act of terror.

00:42:13.060 --> 00:42:17.180
[Guest]: No politician can possibly say that we won't do anything.

00:42:17.180 --> 00:42:18.180
[Guest]: No, no, we must.

00:42:18.180 --> 00:42:21.100
[Guest]: They will have to be seen as doing something.

00:42:21.100 --> 00:42:29.900
[Guest]: So now the use of force is transformed into this ability to strike back, not only to create,

00:42:29.900 --> 00:42:33.140
[Guest]: it will only create a tactical effect in Pakistan.

00:42:33.140 --> 00:42:39.060
[Guest]: But the effect here would actually be what matters politically, which means we have done

00:42:39.060 --> 00:42:40.060
[Amit Varma]: something to them.

00:42:40.060 --> 00:42:44.860
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, a surgical strike against Pakistan might have a limited tactical impact, but

00:42:44.860 --> 00:42:49.460
[Amit Varma]: a greater strategic impact within the Indian discourse, because in terms of optics and

00:42:49.460 --> 00:42:55.300
[Amit Varma]: assuaging the weighing masses, it sort of calms down the lust for war in a sense.

00:42:55.300 --> 00:42:56.620
[Guest]: Yes, it is.

00:42:56.620 --> 00:42:58.020
[Guest]: Unfortunately, that's the case.

00:42:58.020 --> 00:43:03.820
[Guest]: So now, how does the politician therefore control the cycle of revenge?

00:43:03.820 --> 00:43:10.540
[Guest]: So one of the things I say in my book is, we should now, and as the militaries are organized

00:43:10.540 --> 00:43:15.620
[Guest]: at the moment, organized for the big fight, you know, big fights cannot take place.

00:43:15.620 --> 00:43:20.260
[Guest]: So firstly, they have to be restructured, reengineered, and we should have the capability

00:43:20.260 --> 00:43:22.180
[Guest]: to strike without posturing.

00:43:22.180 --> 00:43:27.820
[Guest]: This is the operational shift, which I talk about in my book, that we need to do this.

00:43:27.820 --> 00:43:32.380
[Guest]: We are only meant to, the thing that if anything happens, we must immediately strike back.

00:43:32.380 --> 00:43:37.280
[Guest]: And we hope that with the strike back, the tactical equilibrium is reestablished.

00:43:37.280 --> 00:43:38.900
[Guest]: So you go back to normal.

00:43:38.900 --> 00:43:44.280
[Guest]: So this will have the minimum disturbance on what we should concentrate on, which is

00:43:44.280 --> 00:43:46.120
[Guest]: economic and social development.

00:43:46.120 --> 00:43:49.820
[Guest]: So that's just one of the things which I say.

00:43:49.820 --> 00:43:55.820
[Guest]: But the danger here is how do you play back this retributive act which you have done and

00:43:55.820 --> 00:44:00.540
[Guest]: connect it to your domestic politics.

00:44:00.540 --> 00:44:06.620
[Guest]: The temptation for a government in power is to use it for electoral purposes.

00:44:06.620 --> 00:44:13.300
[Guest]: And that has got potential for taking things out of control.

00:44:13.300 --> 00:44:21.100
[Guest]: Because if you are going to benefit from it electorally, then you would like to play it

00:44:21.100 --> 00:44:28.500
[Guest]: up in such a manner that the other side would want to actually, what do you call, retaliate

00:44:28.500 --> 00:44:29.500
[Guest]: in kind.

00:44:29.500 --> 00:44:31.180
[Guest]: So there is this danger here.

00:44:31.180 --> 00:44:35.200
[Guest]: And what we see of the surgical strikes in the videos which is now coming after, is this

00:44:35.200 --> 00:44:36.200
[Guest]: being played out?

00:44:36.200 --> 00:44:42.540
[Guest]: I mean, the fact is that now it's about how do we get the audience, Indian audience, in

00:44:42.540 --> 00:44:47.780
[Guest]: support and tell them that, you know, and one of the things is there is a lot of emotional

00:44:47.780 --> 00:44:53.020
[Guest]: fuel here, which is in support of the fact that you are acting tough against the Pakistanis.

00:44:53.020 --> 00:45:00.860
[Guest]: Because now in the Indian democratic discourse, any action taken against this great enemy

00:45:00.860 --> 00:45:04.620
[Guest]: of ours has got a lot of power and strengthens the government.

00:45:04.620 --> 00:45:09.780
[Guest]: So here we are, we are in a situation where we are nuclear powers, there is this seduction

00:45:09.780 --> 00:45:13.500
[Guest]: of using force for electoral purposes.

00:45:13.500 --> 00:45:14.500
[Amit Varma]: And that's dangerous.

00:45:14.500 --> 00:45:19.300
[Amit Varma]: I find this incredibly alarming because just the thought of a politician sitting in an

00:45:19.300 --> 00:45:24.700
[Amit Varma]: air-conditioned cabin in New Delhi, looking at his popularity numbers and saying, okay,

00:45:24.700 --> 00:45:31.220
[Amit Varma]: what can I do that will be good optics and using army action as a means to achieve popularity

00:45:31.220 --> 00:45:35.140
[Amit Varma]: among the masses who might be wanting strong action from him is very alarming because the

00:45:35.140 --> 00:45:38.460
[Amit Varma]: question then comes is that, where does he draw the line?

00:45:38.460 --> 00:45:45.060
[Amit Varma]: And if there is a disconnect in his mind between the actual consequences of war, and you know,

00:45:45.060 --> 00:45:47.420
[Amit Varma]: what he's using it for, that's incredibly scary.

00:45:47.420 --> 00:45:48.420
[Amit Varma]: Where does it stop?

00:45:48.420 --> 00:45:50.540
[Guest]: Yeah, I know that's the problem, actually.

00:45:50.540 --> 00:45:56.180
[Guest]: So fundamentally, now it's a question of how do you strike a balance between national interests

00:45:56.180 --> 00:45:58.900
[Guest]: and party interests?

00:45:58.900 --> 00:46:04.900
[Guest]: Can the leadership actually rise above his party interests and look at national interests?

00:46:04.900 --> 00:46:07.820
[Guest]: And that's actually depends upon the type of leadership that we have.

00:46:07.820 --> 00:46:12.060
[Guest]: I'm sure in course of time, we'll find this constantly being played out.

00:46:12.060 --> 00:46:18.460
[Guest]: And it will be interesting to see as to how leadership will learn the lessons.

00:46:18.460 --> 00:46:23.740
[Guest]: The question is, they might start a process which they may not be able to control.

00:46:23.740 --> 00:46:24.860
[Guest]: And that's dangerous.

00:46:24.860 --> 00:46:29.260
[Guest]: So it is better not to start riding the tiger or the horse because you won't know where

00:46:29.260 --> 00:46:30.260
[Guest]: to get off.

00:46:30.260 --> 00:46:34.060
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I find your presumption that such a balance can be struck between political

00:46:34.060 --> 00:46:38.860
[Amit Varma]: interest and national interest to be very idealistic because I don't think such a balance

00:46:38.860 --> 00:46:40.460
[Amit Varma]: can exist.

00:46:40.460 --> 00:46:45.740
[Amit Varma]: The immediate incentives of a Prime Minister will always be to ensure re-election.

00:46:45.740 --> 00:46:48.420
[Amit Varma]: That's pretty much the bottom line with any politician.

00:46:48.420 --> 00:46:54.620
[Amit Varma]: So then the question then comes in, that are our institutions strong enough to withstand

00:46:54.620 --> 00:46:55.620
[Amit Varma]: political pressures?

00:46:55.620 --> 00:46:59.820
[Amit Varma]: Like one of the beautiful things about one of the things which has worked about this

00:46:59.820 --> 00:47:05.780
[Amit Varma]: great Indian experiment is that our army has been sort of kept apart from politics and

00:47:05.780 --> 00:47:10.700
[Amit Varma]: has sort of maintained its distance and its autonomy to a certain extent as compared to

00:47:10.700 --> 00:47:15.860
[Amit Varma]: Pakistan where the army kind of runs the show and is the big, big political force there.

00:47:15.860 --> 00:47:18.420
[Amit Varma]: Do you see that distance under threat?

00:47:18.420 --> 00:47:28.620
[Guest]: See, I think the greater danger lies in the fact that such decisions are made by a small

00:47:28.620 --> 00:47:36.180
[Guest]: oligarchy in the PMO instead of passing it through institutions which have been established.

00:47:36.180 --> 00:47:42.140
[Guest]: We should look at it holistically like the National Security Council, which will look

00:47:42.140 --> 00:47:45.520
[Guest]: at the whole issue of whether what should we do.

00:47:45.520 --> 00:47:47.660
[Guest]: It is established primarily for this purpose.

00:47:47.660 --> 00:47:52.380
[Guest]: If you look at K Subramanian, who actually written about it, and he said there were two

00:47:52.380 --> 00:47:56.320
[Guest]: gives two prime examples of why National Security Council was required.

00:47:56.320 --> 00:48:03.860
[Guest]: It is to prevent individuals or a small oligarchy from making decisions and taking nations down

00:48:03.860 --> 00:48:07.260
[Guest]: a path which actually is not being examined fully.

00:48:07.260 --> 00:48:14.140
[Guest]: And he quotes Rajiv Gandhi's support of the LTT, which was done decision taken by a small

00:48:14.140 --> 00:48:15.140
[Guest]: group of people.

00:48:15.140 --> 00:48:18.340
[Guest]: And he also quotes Indira Gandhi's support of Bindramwale.

00:48:18.340 --> 00:48:23.540
[Guest]: You know, all these two major decisions, if you look at it retrospectively, they were

00:48:23.540 --> 00:48:28.440
[Guest]: decisions which if it was examined carefully, for its repercussions would never have been

00:48:28.440 --> 00:48:29.440
[Guest]: taken.

00:48:29.440 --> 00:48:35.460
[Guest]: So the danger for us is the political leadership not using the institutions which have now

00:48:35.460 --> 00:48:36.460
[Guest]: been put in place.

00:48:36.460 --> 00:48:42.280
[Guest]: And after all, these institutions have been put in place by the Vajpayee government.

00:48:42.280 --> 00:48:45.300
[Guest]: But when you are in power, you can always bypass these institutions.

00:48:45.300 --> 00:48:48.500
[Guest]: And actually, it's not only our country, but happens all over the world.

00:48:48.500 --> 00:48:53.500
[Guest]: If you look at the Americans also, and the decisions taken there, they're not able to

00:48:53.500 --> 00:48:55.700
[Guest]: get something done the way they want to do it.

00:48:55.700 --> 00:48:58.980
[Guest]: They just bypass the institution which is supposed to examine it.

00:48:58.980 --> 00:49:02.840
[Guest]: So we can be no different, but there is a danger lurking there.

00:49:02.840 --> 00:49:07.860
[Amit Varma]: So I'd like to take the subject back to your book, because I think I've done a slide this

00:49:07.860 --> 00:49:12.840
[Amit Varma]: service by going off in with all these general questions and all these general directions.

00:49:12.840 --> 00:49:17.060
[Amit Varma]: Part of your book also while examining your thesis about the possible use of conventional

00:49:17.060 --> 00:49:22.940
[Amit Varma]: forces during nuclear weapons, looks at your lessons from Kargil, your lessons from Parakram,

00:49:22.940 --> 00:49:27.820
[Amit Varma]: where you were a brigade commander, and you said that, you know, had war broken out, that

00:49:27.820 --> 00:49:31.580
[Amit Varma]: would have disproved your thesis and as it happens, that didn't happen.

00:49:31.580 --> 00:49:40.180
[Amit Varma]: So can you tell me a little bit about these sort of these seminal moments where we discovered

00:49:40.180 --> 00:49:47.860
[Amit Varma]: and you could, you know, in the context of your thesis, examine all of these developments?

00:49:47.860 --> 00:49:52.460
[Guest]: Yeah, actually, starting with Kargil.

00:49:52.460 --> 00:49:59.780
[Guest]: Although my research into Kargil indicates to me that Pakistan did not have nuclear weapons,

00:49:59.780 --> 00:50:05.380
[Guest]: operational nuclear weapons, which Musharraf himself has admitted in his book, but the

00:50:05.380 --> 00:50:11.900
[Guest]: Indians I think would have presumed that they have some sort of nuclear capability.

00:50:11.900 --> 00:50:16.220
[Guest]: But it was never discussed in the cabinet.

00:50:16.220 --> 00:50:20.620
[Guest]: The only discussion took place between General Malik and General Malik writes in his book

00:50:20.620 --> 00:50:23.980
[Guest]: between him and Brijesh Mishra, which is outside the cabinet.

00:50:23.980 --> 00:50:30.020
[Guest]: I mean, just in exchange, a discussion between them about the impact of nuclear weapons,

00:50:30.020 --> 00:50:31.220
[Guest]: but there's nothing serious.

00:50:31.220 --> 00:50:37.420
[Guest]: But yet the cabinet imposes a restriction on the armed forces not to cross the L.C.

00:50:37.420 --> 00:50:44.940
[Guest]: I think the more reason for that would have been that India's sensitivity to international

00:50:44.940 --> 00:50:47.660
[Guest]: support for the fight against Pakistan.

00:50:47.660 --> 00:50:51.580
[Guest]: I think that would have been the major, which is weighed on that decision.

00:50:51.580 --> 00:50:55.260
[Guest]: And I may not be nuclear weapons, although we can never be sure of that.

00:50:55.260 --> 00:51:01.100
[Guest]: So Kargil actually is now being quoted as one of the successors of limited war.

00:51:01.100 --> 00:51:09.020
[Guest]: I would agree because in the sense it also tells us that it is a war which is limited

00:51:09.020 --> 00:51:18.700
[Guest]: in geographic space, in quantum of force which was used and also limited in its objective,

00:51:18.700 --> 00:51:22.700
[Guest]: which was just to get the Pakistanis out from the area we occupied.

00:51:22.700 --> 00:51:26.020
[Guest]: This sort of war is possible.

00:51:26.020 --> 00:51:33.420
[Guest]: And that's the type, so border skirmishes, limited geographic wars are what we are going

00:51:33.420 --> 00:51:38.980
[Guest]: to see as the forms of war as far as Pakistan are concerned.

00:51:38.980 --> 00:51:42.140
[Guest]: Primarily because there are nuclear weapons in play.

00:51:42.140 --> 00:51:50.480
[Guest]: So if this is a type of war, then we must also restructure ourselves to fight the type

00:51:50.480 --> 00:51:52.900
[Guest]: of war which we're likely to fight.

00:51:52.900 --> 00:52:00.380
[Guest]: But you know, the problem is that we really do not know and the armies cannot be sure

00:52:00.380 --> 00:52:04.740
[Guest]: as to how a war can start and where it can reach.

00:52:04.740 --> 00:52:10.500
[Guest]: It has to be prepared for the whole hog, because if it is not prepared for the higher level,

00:52:10.500 --> 00:52:12.780
[Guest]: then you might be at a disadvantage.

00:52:12.780 --> 00:52:16.420
[Guest]: So conventional force doesn't go away.

00:52:16.420 --> 00:52:23.040
[Guest]: Conventional force retains its ability to actually have deterrent power.

00:52:23.040 --> 00:52:29.700
[Guest]: That is why having an aircraft carrier, having a fighter aircraft, they've all got tremendous

00:52:29.700 --> 00:52:34.140
[Guest]: optical power, the ability to deter.

00:52:34.140 --> 00:52:40.040
[Guest]: But whether we can use them against an enemy and fight a big war is what is questionable.

00:52:40.040 --> 00:52:45.700
[Guest]: So the paradox is you need all these big things, but you may not be able to use them the way

00:52:45.700 --> 00:52:48.020
[Guest]: that they're meant to be used.

00:52:48.020 --> 00:52:51.980
[Guest]: So at the level of deterrence, there is this need for these sort of...

00:52:51.980 --> 00:52:56.140
[Amit Varma]: You need them to cast a shadow in the enemy's mind, but you're never actually...

00:52:56.140 --> 00:53:00.580
[Guest]: So they're useful for deterrence, but questionable whether we can use them.

00:53:00.580 --> 00:53:03.040
[Amit Varma]: And that's the paradox.

00:53:03.040 --> 00:53:04.140
[Amit Varma]: And what about Parakram?

00:53:04.140 --> 00:53:06.940
[Amit Varma]: Because you were in a sense almost personally involved there.

00:53:06.940 --> 00:53:10.380
[Amit Varma]: And you know, before this podcast started and we were chatting in your cabin, you told

00:53:10.380 --> 00:53:17.140
[Amit Varma]: me about how it was almost a big complicated situation for you because you felt that if

00:53:17.140 --> 00:53:19.500
[Amit Varma]: war breaks out, my thesis will be disproved.

00:53:19.500 --> 00:53:22.340
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, you're preparing for that war and preparing to win it.

00:53:22.340 --> 00:53:25.820
[Guest]: Yeah, you see, I was commanding the Haji Pir Brigade and that brigade is actually what

00:53:25.820 --> 00:53:30.940
[Guest]: is called a core reserve brigade, which means it is the offensive element, one of the offensive

00:53:30.940 --> 00:53:32.660
[Guest]: elements of the core.

00:53:32.660 --> 00:53:37.360
[Guest]: So I have this big plethora of offensive plans, which I make, which is fundamentally about

00:53:37.360 --> 00:53:39.540
[Guest]: capturing territory.

00:53:39.540 --> 00:53:43.420
[Guest]: And so I'm making all these plans and I'm rehearsing them and I'm briefing people and

00:53:43.420 --> 00:53:46.140
[Guest]: briefing this thing is what I'm going to do.

00:53:46.140 --> 00:53:51.780
[Guest]: But in my heart, I have this thesis which says that this sort of war should not actually

00:53:51.780 --> 00:53:52.820
[Guest]: be there.

00:53:52.820 --> 00:53:57.940
[Guest]: So there is a contradiction between my what I do officially and what it is.

00:53:57.940 --> 00:54:03.960
[Guest]: And then finally, I'm proved right because war never takes place because it could not

00:54:03.960 --> 00:54:05.540
[Guest]: have taken place according to my thesis.

00:54:05.540 --> 00:54:08.820
[Guest]: So my thesis survives Parakram.

00:54:08.820 --> 00:54:12.420
[Guest]: And Parakram, therefore, is a good example.

00:54:12.420 --> 00:54:13.420
[Guest]: And we have learned from it.

00:54:13.420 --> 00:54:15.360
[Guest]: But what did we learn?

00:54:15.360 --> 00:54:21.200
[Guest]: Now we learned the lesson was the army took away was that, you know, one of the reasons

00:54:21.200 --> 00:54:25.340
[Guest]: why Parakram didn't take place because we were slow to mobilize.

00:54:25.340 --> 00:54:30.060
[Guest]: We had this very large formations, which we call a strike corps, which took a long time

00:54:30.060 --> 00:54:33.580
[Guest]: to get to the frontier, by which time actually the Pakistanis.

00:54:33.580 --> 00:54:37.680
[Guest]: So that is why was born what is called the Cold Start Doctrine.

00:54:37.680 --> 00:54:43.180
[Guest]: The Cold Start Doctrine believes that we can strike before he gets prepared.

00:54:43.180 --> 00:54:45.180
[Guest]: Basically that's the concept.

00:54:45.180 --> 00:54:50.180
[Guest]: This is another military friction, which can actually it's good to try and scare the other

00:54:50.180 --> 00:54:56.660
[Guest]: through Cold Start because Cold Start means that you have to move formations very close

00:54:56.660 --> 00:54:58.900
[Guest]: to the western border.

00:54:58.900 --> 00:55:03.660
[Guest]: And then you have to apply them very speedily before that guy can actually react.

00:55:03.660 --> 00:55:08.180
[Guest]: But in the Indo-Pak context, it's difficult to do that because when you move from the

00:55:08.180 --> 00:55:13.780
[Guest]: hinterland, all these formations, then Pakistan also can also move them because this you have

00:55:13.780 --> 00:55:17.260
[Guest]: to do in peace because you relocate them.

00:55:17.260 --> 00:55:20.740
[Guest]: And once you relocate them, then nothing stopping from him relocating you.

00:55:20.740 --> 00:55:26.140
[Guest]: So what happened after Cold Start has been in motion for some time now is that both of

00:55:26.140 --> 00:55:30.880
[Guest]: us have relocated some formations and he has also done the same.

00:55:30.880 --> 00:55:36.100
[Guest]: So we are now back to square one and more than anything else, it is a doctrine which

00:55:36.100 --> 00:55:40.800
[Guest]: Pakistan has run with by saying that look at the Indians, they've got this Cold Start

00:55:40.800 --> 00:55:42.760
[Guest]: Doctrine.

00:55:42.760 --> 00:55:45.920
[Guest]: That is why we're saying that they pose a serious threat to us.

00:55:45.920 --> 00:55:52.460
[Guest]: So they've used that threat to increase their own power within the domestic polity and also

00:55:52.460 --> 00:55:57.940
[Guest]: tell the international community, see how the Indians are threatening us and focusing

00:55:57.940 --> 00:56:05.260
[Guest]: attention on the Indo-Pak border, which they want to paint as the most dangerous flashpoint

00:56:05.260 --> 00:56:08.340
[Guest]: in the world because that suits their interests.

00:56:08.340 --> 00:56:12.860
[Amit Varma]: And you know, through this book, it's very interesting to see, you know, your thinking

00:56:12.860 --> 00:56:17.040
[Amit Varma]: on these subjects, but how is the thinking of the Indian Army changed over all of this?

00:56:17.040 --> 00:56:24.380
[Amit Varma]: Because as you pointed out, almost no one was on the side you're on when all this began.

00:56:24.380 --> 00:56:28.940
[Amit Varma]: How has that changed over the years, not just with, you know, new theoretical thinking on

00:56:28.940 --> 00:56:34.160
[Amit Varma]: it such as yours, but also the experience of having gone through Kargil, Parakram, you

00:56:34.160 --> 00:56:38.460
[Amit Varma]: know, the aftermath of the Mumbai attacks?

00:56:38.460 --> 00:56:46.100
[Guest]: The point I make in my book is, the Army has no other choice but try to see as to how they

00:56:46.100 --> 00:56:49.920
[Guest]: can make themselves relevant in this situation.

00:56:49.920 --> 00:56:55.500
[Guest]: I do not see any major restructuring which the armed forces has done to make them relevant,

00:56:55.500 --> 00:57:02.100
[Guest]: except for this Cold Start doctrine, which I think is military fiction.

00:57:02.100 --> 00:57:10.180
[Guest]: So the Army has been trying to discover operational virtuosity, which is the word I use, to see

00:57:10.180 --> 00:57:13.420
[Guest]: as to how we can overcome this problem.

00:57:13.420 --> 00:57:20.740
[Guest]: But my point is that such operational virtuosity cannot exist in the structural situation India

00:57:20.740 --> 00:57:22.500
[Guest]: finds itself.

00:57:22.500 --> 00:57:27.260
[Guest]: Between the fact that this is what the geography is, the nuclear weapons are there, that structural

00:57:27.260 --> 00:57:33.180
[Guest]: situation is not redeemable through operational virtuosity.

00:57:33.180 --> 00:57:34.680
[Guest]: You have no choice.

00:57:34.680 --> 00:57:39.660
[Guest]: You have to make the political leaders understand what force is meant for, what it's possible

00:57:39.660 --> 00:57:45.060
[Guest]: for them to do, and you need a dialogue to make that happen.

00:57:45.060 --> 00:57:48.380
[Guest]: But in the Indian instance, that dialogue is not there.

00:57:48.380 --> 00:57:52.740
[Guest]: That dialogue is spasmodic if it ever exists.

00:57:52.740 --> 00:57:59.780
[Guest]: So the politicians, when it comes to it, will probably be episodic to a particular situation,

00:57:59.780 --> 00:58:02.740
[Guest]: then forget about it because they move on to many other things.

00:58:02.740 --> 00:58:11.820
[Guest]: So we suffer now from a systemic problem that we have yet to crystallize.

00:58:11.820 --> 00:58:15.060
[Guest]: What do we need the armed forces for?

00:58:15.060 --> 00:58:17.260
[Guest]: What is the political objectives we need to reach?

00:58:17.260 --> 00:58:22.260
[Guest]: That is why we don't have a national strategy, neither do we have a military strategy, because

00:58:22.260 --> 00:58:27.020
[Guest]: all this has to come from the fact that what does India want to do?

00:58:27.020 --> 00:58:29.860
[Guest]: What sort of military power do we want?

00:58:29.860 --> 00:58:35.620
[Guest]: The meta question, how do we balance our continental and maritime power?

00:58:35.620 --> 00:58:41.380
[Guest]: Because it is obvious to us that as far as international politics is concerned, maritime

00:58:41.380 --> 00:58:44.580
[Guest]: power will be the ones which we can make a difference.

00:58:44.580 --> 00:58:48.700
[Guest]: Continental power is where we can't project power because we are locked here with Pakistan

00:58:48.700 --> 00:58:53.500
[Guest]: and nuclear power, with China and the mountains and so on.

00:58:53.500 --> 00:58:59.500
[Guest]: So we have to make this decision about how do we shape the military instrument.

00:58:59.500 --> 00:59:06.020
[Guest]: India, because of its institutional inadequacies, have not been able to make these decisions.

00:59:06.020 --> 00:59:09.500
[Guest]: And therefore we continue to actually do it in parts.

00:59:09.500 --> 00:59:14.060
[Amit Varma]: And would it then be correct to say that because we are a nuclear power facing other nuclear

00:59:14.060 --> 00:59:18.060
[Amit Varma]: powers like Pakistan and China, especially Pakistan, we are stuck between a rock and

00:59:18.060 --> 00:59:19.060
[Amit Varma]: a hard place.

00:59:19.060 --> 00:59:23.300
[Amit Varma]: On the one hand, we have nuclear weapons, but everybody knows that our whole objective

00:59:23.300 --> 00:59:26.820
[Amit Varma]: is not to use them and therefore we are going to be very restrained.

00:59:26.820 --> 00:59:31.140
[Amit Varma]: And on the other hand, because we have those nuclear weapons, we cannot use conventional

00:59:31.140 --> 00:59:36.260
[Amit Varma]: forces beyond a certain threshold, as you point out, which is why Parakram didn't happen

00:59:36.260 --> 00:59:41.020
[Amit Varma]: and Kargil is pretty much an exemplar of the kind of force that can be used, but no more

00:59:41.020 --> 00:59:42.660
[Amit Varma]: than that.

00:59:42.660 --> 00:59:46.260
[Amit Varma]: It then strikes me as a dilemma that, like you said, what is the role of the military?

00:59:46.260 --> 00:59:47.260
[Guest]: Yeah, you're right.

00:59:47.260 --> 00:59:48.580
[Guest]: You're right.

00:59:48.580 --> 00:59:56.460
[Guest]: So the challenge for the military is, the fact is that force does not going to go away.

00:59:56.460 --> 01:00:01.620
[Guest]: It has to change its forms to suit the situation.

01:00:01.620 --> 01:00:08.300
[Guest]: Today, that force, which we call the kinetic force, is now sort of morphed itself into

01:00:08.300 --> 01:00:09.420
[Guest]: many other ways.

01:00:09.420 --> 01:00:15.140
[Guest]: And cyber actually is a good example of what is possible.

01:00:15.140 --> 01:00:24.180
[Guest]: Therefore, India has to identify those capacities and therefore use those capacities for the

01:00:24.180 --> 01:00:35.900
[Guest]: ability to either destroy, hurt or cause pain, which can be used and identify the types of

01:00:35.900 --> 01:00:40.180
[Guest]: war for which it should be prepared to fight.

01:00:40.180 --> 01:00:48.900
[Guest]: I'm afraid that the armed forces continue to be focused on what is called the Napoleonic

01:00:48.900 --> 01:00:55.620
[Guest]: era of the decisive battle, where you bring the armed forces of the others to a decisive

01:00:55.620 --> 01:00:58.740
[Guest]: battle and beat them conclusively.

01:00:58.740 --> 01:01:05.460
[Guest]: We have to get out of that mindset and look to the present, the contemporary era, to how

01:01:05.460 --> 01:01:11.260
[Guest]: do we now identify the types of war we must be ready to fight.

01:01:11.260 --> 01:01:17.020
[Guest]: So you have types of war and at the same time, how do we actually manage the issue of deterrence

01:01:17.020 --> 01:01:23.860
[Guest]: where you need optical power, which is what China does very well, where you need these

01:01:23.860 --> 01:01:28.060
[Guest]: big guys, you can't say that you don't need aircraft carriers or so on.

01:01:28.060 --> 01:01:29.760
[Guest]: They all have their uses.

01:01:29.760 --> 01:01:30.760
[Guest]: So you need both.

01:01:30.760 --> 01:01:36.460
[Guest]: The question is, how do you mesh these two and make it into a coherent strategy, which

01:01:36.460 --> 01:01:41.660
[Guest]: must be a military strategy, not an army, air force or a naval strategy.

01:01:41.660 --> 01:01:42.660
[Guest]: That is what we have.

01:01:42.660 --> 01:01:47.460
[Guest]: Unfortunately, our structures as we are now, we don't have a CDS and you know, the state

01:01:47.460 --> 01:01:50.780
[Guest]: in which the MOD is, none of these things are possible.

01:01:50.780 --> 01:01:55.100
[Guest]: So we continue to function in silos.

01:01:55.100 --> 01:02:01.180
[Guest]: And that I think is a great bane because strategy requires the understanding of the nature of

01:02:01.180 --> 01:02:03.380
[Guest]: the whole as Clausewitz would have put it.

01:02:03.380 --> 01:02:04.380
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:02:04.380 --> 01:02:05.900
[Amit Varma]: It's been a fascinating discussion.

01:02:05.900 --> 01:02:10.340
[Amit Varma]: And I'm going to end with asking you two questions that I ask all my guests on the subject of

01:02:10.340 --> 01:02:12.380
[Amit Varma]: expertise.

01:02:12.380 --> 01:02:17.620
[Amit Varma]: What makes you hopeful and what makes you despair about the changing nature of war in

01:02:17.620 --> 01:02:19.700
[Guest]: this nuclear age?

01:02:19.700 --> 01:02:32.260
[Guest]: Hopeful that we will keep our ambitions in check, because there is a danger that we might

01:02:32.260 --> 01:02:37.820
[Guest]: cross the line which we do not want and get hurt more than what we actually that danger

01:02:37.820 --> 01:02:43.300
[Guest]: that the very fact that uncertainty will keep ambitions in check.

01:02:43.300 --> 01:02:49.820
[Guest]: So force will not be used the way it has been used through centuries, which is when we disagree,

01:02:49.820 --> 01:02:51.500
[Guest]: then I take it forcefully from you.

01:02:51.500 --> 01:02:55.820
[Guest]: You know, that's one of the things which makes me hopeful.

01:02:55.820 --> 01:03:01.020
[Guest]: But the larger issue now is, if you look at the world today, and if you see the confrontation

01:03:01.020 --> 01:03:10.900
[Guest]: building up with global geopolitics and even Asian geopolitics, the danger of a clash between

01:03:10.900 --> 01:03:14.940
[Guest]: the big guys is increasing.

01:03:14.940 --> 01:03:19.860
[Guest]: Both of them are very cognizant of the fact that in the previous era, when these sort

01:03:19.860 --> 01:03:24.900
[Guest]: of things took place, you could go to war and they would be you would arrive finally,

01:03:24.900 --> 01:03:30.500
[Guest]: however painfully at some sort of an equilibrium, which that war would bring about.

01:03:30.500 --> 01:03:36.540
[Guest]: But the now the problem is that you can't go to war in that manner.

01:03:36.540 --> 01:03:39.900
[Guest]: So nations have been going to war through proxies.

01:03:39.900 --> 01:03:42.420
[Guest]: And that's been the way it's done.

01:03:42.420 --> 01:03:48.620
[Guest]: But the danger is that today, the pace at which wars are going to be conducted, the

01:03:48.620 --> 01:03:54.780
[Guest]: sheer speed at which you're going to exchange energy would would actually enmesh the military

01:03:54.780 --> 01:04:01.700
[Guest]: so fast that it can go easily out of political control, that the whole grammar of war will

01:04:01.700 --> 01:04:06.420
[Guest]: actually drive the momentum of war, and it will lose political control.

01:04:06.420 --> 01:04:13.180
[Guest]: And when war loses political control and is overtaken by military logic, then we are in

01:04:13.180 --> 01:04:14.180
[Guest]: danger.

01:04:14.180 --> 01:04:16.020
[Amit Varma]: So that is my despair.

01:04:16.020 --> 01:04:20.340
[Amit Varma]: With that incredibly horrifying and scary thought, let me thank you so much, General

01:04:20.340 --> 01:04:21.660
[Guest]: Menon for coming on the show.

01:04:21.660 --> 01:04:22.660
[Guest]: Thank you very much.

01:04:22.660 --> 01:04:23.740
[Guest]: It's been a great pleasure.

01:04:23.740 --> 01:04:53.060
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

